stories for the Many examines the contribution of illustrated family magazines to Victorian historical culture. How, by whom, for whom and with which intentions was history used within this popular medium? How were class, gender, age, religion, and space debated? How were academic and popular approaches to the past linked to the materiality of the medium? The focus is set on the evangelical Leisure Hour with comparisons to the London Journal, Good Words and Cornhill. The study's approach to the serialisation of history in text and image combines periodical studies and book history with concepts from cultural studies, sociology as well as narratology.  afunded by Deutsche Forschungsgemeinschaft (DFG)  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aEnglish periodicals. 0aHistory in popular culture. 0aHistoryvPeriodicals. 0aPopular culturezEnglandxHistoryy19th century. 4a19th Century. 4aBritish History. 4aCultural History. 4aEngland. 4aHistorical Culture. 4aHistory. 4aMedia. 4aMemory Culture. 4aPopular Culture. 4aPopular History. 4aSocial History. 4aVictorian Culture. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh  a19th Century.  aBritish History.  aCultural History.  aEngland.  aHistorical Culture.  aHistory.  aMedia.  aMemory Culture.  aPopular Culture.  aPopular History.  aSocial History.  aVictorian Culture.2 aDeutsche Forschungsgemeinschaft (DFG)efunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2016z978311070100508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2016z9783110485189oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPP Plus eBook-Package 2016z978311070